│ I'll help you troubleshoot this NVIDIA SDK Manager installation failure.    │
│ Let me start by analyzing the log and searching for solutions.              │
│                                                                             │
│ ## Diagnosis                                                                │
│                                                                             │
│ The log shows a kernel module loading failure at the NVIDIA driver          │
│ installation stage. Specifically:                                           │
│ - **Line 1:** `modprobe: ERROR: could not insert 'nvgpu': Exec format       │
│ error`                                                                      │
│ - **Line 2:** `NVIDIA driver installation failed: kernel module nvgpu could │
│ not be loaded`                                                              │
│                                                                             │
│ The "Exec format error" indicates the nvgpu kernel module binary is         │
│ incompatible with the running kernel—likely a mismatch between the module's │
│ architecture/version and the kernel it's being loaded into.                 │
│                                                                             │
│ Now let me search for expert solutions:                                     │
│                                                                             │
│ These results are about desktop NVIDIA drivers and the `nvidia` module, not │
│ the `nvgpu` module. Let me search more specifically for nvgpu and           │
│ JetPack/Jetson contexts:                                                    │
│                                                                             │
│ Based on the sources I've found, the key issue is kernel/module mismatch in │
│ JetPack environments. Let me provide the diagnosis and fix:                 │
│                                                                             │
│ ## Diagnosis                                                                │
│                                                                             │
│ The log shows a kernel module loading failure during NVIDIA driver          │
│ installation on a Jetson device (indicated by the `nvgpu` module, which is  │
│ specific to Jetson platforms):                                              │
│                                                                             │
│ - **Line 1:** `modprobe: ERROR: could not insert 'nvgpu': Exec format       │
│ error`                                                                      │
│ - **Line 2:** `NVIDIA driver installation failed: kernel module nvgpu could │
│ not be loaded`                                                              │
│                                                                             │
│ The "Exec format error" (ELF format mismatch) indicates that the `nvgpu.ko` │
│ binary was compiled for a different kernel version or configuration than    │
│ the one currently running. This is the most common cause when JetPack       │
│ modules are manually installed or when custom kernels are used without      │
│ properly rebuilding the out-of-tree modules (like nvgpu).                   │
│                                                                             │
│ ## Recommended fix                                                          │
│                                                                             │
│ ```bash                                                                     │
│ # 1. Check the running kernel version                                       │
│ uname -r                                                                    │
│                                                                             │
│ # 2. Check the module compatibility                                         │
│ file /lib/modules/$(uname -r)/kernel/drivers/gpu/nvgpu/nvgpu.ko             │
│                                                                             │
│ # 3. Verify kernel headers are installed                                    │
│ ls /lib/modules/$(uname -r)/build                                           │
│                                                                             │
│ # 4. If using JetPack with a custom kernel, rebuild nvgpu from source:      │
│ cd <path_to_nvgpu_source>                                                   │
│ make ARCH=arm64 -C /lib/modules/$(uname -r)/build M=$(pwd) clean            │
│ make ARCH=arm64 -C /lib/modules/$(uname -r)/build M=$(pwd)                  │
│ sudo make ARCH=arm64 -C /lib/modules/$(uname -r)/build M=$(pwd)             │
│ modules_install                                                             │
│                                                                             │
│ # 5. Reload the module                                                      │
│ sudo depmod -a                                                              │
│ sudo modprobe nvgpu                                                         │
│ ```                                                                         │
│                                                                             │
│ ## Why this works                                                           │
│                                                                             │
│                                                                             │
│                                                                             │
│ The nvgpu.ko module must match the kernel it runs on                        │
│                                                                             │
│ , and                                                                       │
│                                                                             │
│ JetPack firmware is incompatible with kernels of different versions         │
│                                                                             │
│ . The "Exec format error" occurs when the module's binary architecture or   │
│ kernel ABI (Application Binary Interface) does not match the running        │
│ kernel.                                                                     │
│                                                                             │
│ When building out-of-tree kernel modules on JetPack, the correct approach   │
│ is to build against the actual kernel headers                               │
│                                                                             │
│  using `make ARCH=arm64 -C <kernel_directory> M=$(pwd)`. The `depmod -a`    │
│ command rebuilds the kernel module dependency database, and `modprobe       │
│ nvgpu` attempts to load the freshly built module against the correct        │
│ kernel.                                                                     │
│                                                                             │
│ **Sources:**                                                                │
│ https://docs.nvidia.com/jetson/archives/r35.3.1/DeveloperGuide/text/SD/Kern │
│ el/KernelCustomization.html, https://github.com/anduril/jetpack-nixos,      │
│ https://docs.nvidia.com/jetson/archives/r35.1/DeveloperGuide/text/SD/Kernel │
│ /KernelCustomization.html                                                   │
│                                                                             │
│ ## Risks / when not to run                                                  │
│                                                                             │
│ **Critical:** Steps 4–5 require `sudo` and modify kernel module paths.      │
│ Running these on a production system may cause temporary driver             │
│ unavailability until the build completes. If you are cross-compiling (e.g., │
│ building on an x86_64 host for Jetson), ensure the `CROSS_COMPILE`          │
│ environment variable is set properly and that you have the correct ARM64    │
│ toolchain installed; otherwise the rebuilt module will fail again. Do       │
│ **not** delete `/lib/modules/$(uname -r)/` entirely, as it will render the  │
│ system unbootable. If you do not have kernel source available               │
│ (nvgpu_source), you may need to reinstall JetPack entirely via `SDKManager` │
│ or reflash the board with a clean JetPack image.                            │
