│ df -h ~                                                                     │
│                                                                             │
│ # If low on space, clear temporary files                                    │
│ sudo apt clean                                                              │
│ sudo apt autoclean                                                          │
│                                                                             │
│ # Optionally: restart the system before retrying                            │
│ sudo reboot                                                                 │
│ ```                                                                         │
│                                                                             │
│ ## Why this works                                                           │
│                                                                             │
│                                                                             │
│                                                                             │
│ Users on the NVIDIA Developer Forums have confirmed that removing the       │
│ `.nvsdkm` directory resolves configuration and download state issues        │
│                                                                             │
│ . Deleting `~/.nvsdkm` forces SDK Manager to reinitialize its cache and     │
│ metadata on the next launch, which clears any stale or corrupted state.     │
│ Removing the `sdkm_downloads` folder ensures that the next download is      │
│ performed fresh from NVIDIA's servers with full checksum re-verification.   │
│                                                                             │
│ The default download path is `/home/$USER/Downloads/nvidia/sdkm_downloads`  │
│                                                                             │
│ , and removing partial or corrupted archives there prevents checksum        │
│ mismatches.                                                                 │
│                                                                             │
│ For additional context, see the NVIDIA SDK Manager official docs:           │
│ https://docs.nvidia.com/sdk-manager/install-with-sdkm-jetson/index.html     │
│                                                                             │
│ ## Risks / when not to run                                                  │
│                                                                             │
│ - **No sudo required for user home cleanup** — the commands above only      │
│ delete your own cache directories and are safe.                             │
│ - **Network dependency** — a full re-download of JetPack 6.1 (~5–15 GB)     │
│ will occur; ensure a stable internet connection.                            │
│ - **Time cost** — re-download and checksum verification may take 15–45      │
│ minutes depending on bandwidth.                                             │
│ - **Do not use `sudo rm`** on `~/.nvsdkm` or the Downloads folder unless    │
│ you own them; verify ownership first with `ls -la ~/.nvsdkm`.               │
│ - **Backup before deleting** — if you have custom SDK Manager settings,     │
│ export logs first via the GUI menu before deleting `~/.nvsdkm`.             │
