│                                                                             │
│ ## Diagnosis                                                                │
│                                                                             │
│                                                                             │
│                                                                             │
│ The log shows: `E: Could not get lock /var/lib/dpkg/lock - open (11:        │
│ Resource temporarily unavailable)` during the `target_install` (apt) stage  │
│                                                                             │
│ . This indicates that the `apt` package manager on the target Jetson device │
│ cannot acquire exclusive access to the dpkg lock file because another       │
│ process is holding it.                                                      │
│                                                                             │
│ This typically occurs when a previous apt command was not terminated        │
│ properly and the lock files were not deleted                                │
│                                                                             │
│ , or because                                                                │
│                                                                             │
│ the package repository index update is executed automatically by the system │
│ in the background                                                           │
│                                                                             │
│ .                                                                           │
│                                                                             │
│ ## Recommended fix                                                          │
│                                                                             │
│ **On the target Jetson device (via SSH or serial console):**                │
│                                                                             │
│ ```bash                                                                     │
│ # 1. Check if any apt/dpkg processes are still running                      │
│ ps aux | grep -E 'apt|dpkg' | grep -v grep                                  │
│                                                                             │
│ # 2. If processes are running, wait for them to complete, then proceed      │
│ # If they appear stuck, kill them (use with caution):                       │
│ sudo killall apt apt-get dpkg 2>/dev/null                                   │
│                                                                             │
│ # 3. Remove stale lock files                                                │
│ sudo rm /var/lib/dpkg/lock                                                  │
│ sudo rm /var/lib/dpkg/lock-frontend                                         │
│ sudo rm /var/lib/apt/lists/lock                                             │
│ sudo rm /var/cache/apt/archives/lock                                        │
│                                                                             │
│ # 4. Reconfigure dpkg to clean up any partial state                         │
│ sudo dpkg --configure -a                                                    │
│                                                                             │
│ # 5. Verify apt is working                                                  │
│ sudo apt update                                                             │
│                                                                             │
│ # 6. Then retry the SDK Manager installation                                │
│ ```                                                                         │
│                                                                             │
│ ## Why this works                                                           │
│                                                                             │
│                                                                             │
│                                                                             │
│ The "Resource temporarily unavailable" error occurs when another process is │
│ using /var/lib/dpkg/lock. The fix is to remove these stale lock files and   │
│ reconfigure dpkg                                                            │
│                                                                             │
│ .                                                                           │
│                                                                             │
│ The simplest recommended solution is to wait and let the background package │
│ management tool finish its work and release the lock file                   │
│                                                                             │
│ . If waiting doesn't work,                                                  │
│                                                                             │
│ removing the lock files of dpkg by running `sudo rm                         │
│ /var/lib/apt/lists/lock`, `sudo rm /var/cache/apt/archives/lock`, and `sudo │
│ rm /var/lib/dpkg/lock`                                                      │
│                                                                             │
│  is the standard approach. This issue has been documented in the NVIDIA     │
│ developer forums for multiple JetPack versions (see                         │
│ https://forums.developer.nvidia.com/t/error-installing-jetpack-6-2-1/337555 │
│ ).                                                                          │
│                                                                             │
│ ## Risks / when not to run                                                  │
│                                                                             │
│ ⚠️ **`sudo rm` commands are destructive.** Only execute step 3 if:          │
│ - You've confirmed no apt/dpkg processes are actively running (step 1)      │
│ - Or you've killed stuck processes (step 2)                                 │
│                                                                             │
│ If you run `rm` while apt is actively writing to the dpkg database, you may │
│ corrupt the package manager state. After removing locks, always run `sudo   │
│ dpkg --configure -a` (step 4) to restore consistency. Do not reboot between │
│ lock removal and reconfiguration.                                           │
