│ Perfect. I now have comprehensive expert guidance from multiple             │
│ authoritative sources. Let me compile the diagnosis and fix.                │
│                                                                             │
│ ---                                                                         │
│                                                                             │
│ ## Diagnosis                                                                │
│                                                                             │
│                                                                             │
│                                                                             │
│ The log shows the kernel activated its read-only file system protection     │
│ mechanism, which occurs when Ubuntu detects an inconsistency in the file    │
│ system metadata or a hardware failure                                       │
│                                                                             │
│ . Specifically, the message **"Read-only file system"** followed by         │
│ **"Install aborted at stage: postinst"** indicates that during the          │
│ post-installation phase (when SDK Manager's Debian package scripts were     │
│ attempting to write configuration files, create directories, or modify      │
│ system settings), the kernel had already locked the filesystem to read-only │
│ mode to prevent catastrophic data loss. This is a protective measure, not   │
│ an SDK Manager issue—the installer cannot proceed when the target           │
│ filesystem lacks write permissions.                                         │
│                                                                             │
│ ## Recommended fix                                                          │
│                                                                             │
│ The standard fix follows this sequence:                                     │
│                                                                             │
│ ```bash                                                                     │
│ # 1. Identify your root partition (usually /dev/sda1, but verify)           │
│ lsblk -f                                                                    │
│ # or                                                                        │
│ df /                                                                        │
│                                                                             │
│ # 2. Attempt a simple remount to rw first (may work for temporary issues)   │
│ sudo mount -o remount,rw /                                                  │
│                                                                             │
│ # 3. If step 2 fails, you must repair the filesystem from a safe            │
│ environment.                                                                │
│ # Boot from a live USB/CD with a Linux distribution (Ubuntu Live ISO        │
│ works).                                                                     │
│ # Then run fsck on the UNMOUNTED partition.                                 │
│ # Replace /dev/sda1 with your actual root partition from step 1:            │
│                                                                             │
│ # First, do a read-only check (safe, no changes)                            │
│ sudo fsck -n /dev/sda1                                                      │
│                                                                             │
│ # If errors are found, repair automatically with:                           │
│ sudo fsck -y /dev/sda1                                                      │
│                                                                             │
│ # 4. Once fsck completes successfully, remount and retry SDK Manager        │
│ install:                                                                    │
│ sudo mount -o remount,rw /                                                  │
│ sudo reboot                                                                 │
│ ```                                                                         │
│                                                                             │
│ ## Why this works                                                           │
│                                                                             │
│                                                                             │
│                                                                             │
│ A "Read-Only" file system is a self-preservation mechanism triggered by the │
│ Linux kernel to prevent catastrophic data loss                              │
│                                                                             │
│ , and                                                                       │
│                                                                             │
│ if you see this error, stop writing data immediately and do not simply      │
│ "Remount RW" without first verifying the structural integrity of the drive  │
│ via fsck from a Live USB                                                    │
│                                                                             │
│  (per                                                                       │
│ https://www.fosslinux.com/110294/how-to-fix-the-read-only-file-system-error │
│ -on-ubuntu.htm).                                                            │
│                                                                             │
│                                                                             │
│                                                                             │
│ To fix the issue, you must re-mount the file system to get permission       │
│                                                                             │
│ , and                                                                       │
│                                                                             │
│ running fsck on a mounted partition can cause severe data corruption, so    │
│ always unmount the partition first                                          │
│                                                                             │
│  (per https://www.tecmint.com/fsck-repair-file-system-errors-in-linux/).    │
│                                                                             │
│ The -p option tells fsck to automatically repair any problems that can be   │
│ safely fixed without user intervention. Once the filesystem is repaired,    │
│ mount the partition                                                         │
│                                                                             │
│  (per https://linuxize.com/post/fsck-command-in-linux/). After repair, the  │
│ post-install scripts will have write access and SDK Manager can complete.   │
│                                                                             │
│ ## Risks / when not to run                                                  │
│                                                                             │
│ **WARNING: These are destructive/sudo commands.**                           │
│                                                                             │
│ - **`fsck -y`** automatically answers "yes" to all repairs; it modifies the │
│ filesystem. Only use after a read-only check (`-n` flag) confirms           │
│ corruption.                                                                 │
│ - **Never run `fsck` on a mounted filesystem**—it will corrupt data.        │
│                                                                             │
│ Never run fsck on a mounted partition                                       │
│                                                                             │
│  (per https://www.tecmint.com/fsck-repair-file-system-errors-in-linux/).    │
│ You **must boot from a live USB** or use recovery mode.                     │
│ - The `mount -o remount,rw` step may fail silently if the filesystem        │
│ corruption is severe; if so, you **must** run fsck.                         │
│ - If you are unfamiliar with identifying your root partition, run `lsblk    │
│ -f` or `df /` first—installing fsck on the wrong device is catastrophic.    │
│                                                                             │
│ After repair completes, the SDK Manager installation can be retried.        │
